NAME
       hulak - User friendly API Client for terminal nerds

SYNOPSIS
       hulak [OPTIONS] -f <file>
       hulak [OPTIONS] -fp <file_path>
       hulak migrate <json_file>

DESCRIPTION
       Hulak is a user-friendly API client that supports multiple HTTP methods and allows for easy API testing and integration using YAML configuration files.

OPTIONS
       -env <environment>
              Specify the environment file inside the env directory to use for API calls. If not provided, defaults to global.

       -f <file>
              YAML/YML file to run. Hulak recurses directories to find the matching file and executes it. If multiple matches are found, Hulak runs all concurrently.

       -fp <file_path>
              Specify the exact file path to run.

       migrate <json_file>
              Specify the JSON file to migrate to Hulak.

FLAGS
       -env   Specify the environment file for API calls.
       -f     YAML/YML file to run.
       -fp    File path for the file to run.

INSTALLATION
       Install Hulak via `go install` or build from source.

       go install:
              go install github.com/xaaha/hulak@latest
              Add GOPATH to shellâ€™s PATH:
              export GOPATH=$HOME/go
              export PATH=$PATH:$(go env GOPATH)/bin
              source ~/.zshrc or source ~/.bashrc
Build from source:
              git clone https://github.com/xaaha/hulak.git
              cd hulak
              go mod tidy
              go build -o hulak
              sudo mv hulak /usr/local/bin/

ENVIRONMENT SETUP
       Create `env/` directory and `global.env` file in the root of the project.

       mkdir -p env && touch env/global.env

EXAMPLES
       Basic API call:
              # test.yaml
              method: GET
              url: https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1

              Run with:
              hulak -f test

       Using environment variables:
              # test.yaml
              method: POST
              url: "{{.Url}}"

              Run with:
              hulak -env prod -f test

